---
const problems = [
  {
    title: 'Dead zones everywhere',
    description: 'The basement, the garage, the back bedroom — there\'s always a spot where Wi-Fi just doesn\'t reach. One router in the corner of your house was never going to cut it.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Constant rebooting',
    description: 'When "restart the router" is your go-to fix, something\'s wrong. Devices dropping off, buffering during calls, speeds that don\'t match what you\'re paying for.',
  },
  {
    title: 'ISP hardware you\'re stuck with',
    description: 'The combo box your provider installed tries to be a router, a switch, and a Wi-Fi access point all at once. It\'s not great at any of them.',
  },
];
---

<section id="problem" class="py-24 px-6">
  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
    <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-4 text-center">Why most home networks suck</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-center mb-16 max-w-xl mx-auto">It's not your fault — the default setup was never designed for how you actually use your network.</p>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      {problems.map(p => (
        <div class="bg-white/[0.03] border border-white/[0.06] rounded-2xl p-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-3">{p.title}</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">{p.description}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
